problem.markdown:
>>We are interested in solving the task of automatically recognizing flowers in images. We limit the number of flower species to 1000. We have 10 labeled images per species and many unlabeled images of flowers. What is the best learning framework to address this problem?<<

( ) Supervised learning {{The number of labeled images is too low for fully supervised learning.}}
(x) Semi-supervised learning {{By using techniques in semi-supervised learning to leverage the value of the unlabeled images, you maximize your chance to train a good mode.l}}
( ) Active learning {{It is not clear from the context that the expert is available to label more examples.}}
( ) Self-supervised learning {{Self-supervised learning can be used, but in general, the idea behind self-supervised learning is that the downstream tasks are not known, and so, the labeled dataset is not used during training. In our context, the downstream task is known, and we should use the labeled data as much as possible.}}

||Think about how you can leverage the information contained in the unlabeled examples.||
